\morph -d
\morph -c
\morph -ʔ
\morph -iʔ
\alt -hai
\alt -ar
\alt -r
\ps v2
\mtyp v2
\de COMPL.ITR completive intransitive
\seme The basic meaning of this V2 seems to be movement away from some place. More abstract meanings become possible via metaphoric extension. In some cases -hat(t) comes very close to a completive aspect marker. It is easy to confuse with -dhend (6697) in this function, but the two are complementarily distributed with many verbs and yield slightly differently meanings where they are not. 
\gn भइहाल्नु
\lg C
\ety cf. khat- ‘go’
\com The shortened forms without onset can be used anywhere but are obligatory after vowels (except in a_C). 
\qst

