\lex -kha
\ps gm
\mtyp affix
\de LOC
\seme an areal or directional locative; can often be translated as ‘around’, ‘across’
\gn तिर; वरिपरि
\lg C
\ex Hana yaŋ dui car barsa bakhai ta yuwa kha na.
\exe You should also stay around here for two or four years.
\exn तिमी पनि दुई चार बर्ष यहिं नै बसिहेर त ।
\exsrc chintang_sahid.158
\com only in combination with locative markers -iʔ or (rarely) -peʔ.
\qst

\lex -kha
\alt -ha
\alt -khaʔ
\alt -kkha
\alt -pha
\ps gm
\mtyp affix
\de NMLZ
\seme This word serves a great many functions, the common denominator of which is something like non-specific categorisation. The word to the left of -kha (noun, verb, and many other POS are possible) is marked as categorising something else, e.g. a referent to the right (adnominal categorisation), a referent to the left (copular-like function, marking rheme), or the general situation (marking causal or temporal backgrounds). 
\gn जे; जो; हुनु
\lg C
\ex Inap attakha boŋgi lonno lou.
\exe Now a big bubble of snot is coming out of your nose.
\exn तिम्रो सिंगानको फोका निस्कन्छ है !
\exsrc CLLDCh3R09S08.0269
\ex Baisakh 13 gate munduŋnɨŋkha samaya lisaŋse.
\exe Baisakh 13 has become a date I shall never forget.
\exn बैसाख १३ गते बिर्सनै नसकिने समय भएको छ ।
\exsrc sadstory_RM.019 - 021
\ex Inɨŋ themkha?
\exe What's your name?
\exn तपाईंको नाम के हो ?
\exsrc field notes ROS
\ex Hun na cãdikha.
\exe That one is made of silver.
\exn त्यो त चाँदी हो ।
\exsrc CLLDCh2R11S06.058
\ex Yoba chuda, phak ummaŋa na maineknokha lo naŋ!
\exe Tether it over there, the pig's mother bites, you know!
\exn पर बाँध, माउ सुँगुरले त टोक्छ पो !
\exsrc CLLDCh1R09S06.0303
\ex Huŋgo hanaiko idhokukha?
\exe So this is your basket?
\exn त्यो तिम्रो डोको हो ?
\exsrc CLLDCh1R02S04.0740
\ex Meĩceŋa napattakha pho naŋ.
\exe They said they had invited you.
\exn उनीहरूले तिमीलाई बोलाएका थिए अरे ।
\exsrc them_talk.049
\ex Khoŋsɨŋ lettaŋsaŋkha.
\exe I've planted soy beans.
\exn भटमास रोपेकी छु ।
\exsrc CLDLCh2R02S02.163
\com sometimes the modified noun is covert, e.g. imkha (thaũ) ‘sleeping place’. This is not a suffix by the criterion of host selection (it can occur with nominals, verbs, and adverbs) but still is analysed as a suffix here because it can attach to true suffixes which would otherwise be separated from their host by a morphological gap (as in lamo kha-ce 'long ones'). 
\qst

