\lex luŋmak
\alt luŋma
\ps n
\mtyp stem
\de heart
\gn मुटु
\lg C
\qst most corpus instances have मुटु, but there is one where definitely the organ and not an emotion is referred to and where the translation is कलेजो. In Yakkha the meaning of the word is कलेजो rather than मुटु , and मुटु is an erroneous translation based on the fact that the heart rather than the liver is viewed as the origin of human emotions in Nepali. The transcribers also suggested कलेजो, but this is also their translation for coʔwa, which they translate as 'heart' in another line in the same question file, so they are probably simply clueless. मुटु has been chosen as the final translation because it was in the community dictionary and because luŋmak is the only word that CAN be translated as 'heart' (meaning that if luŋmak wasn't 'heart' there wouldn't be a word for 'heart').

