\lex mett
\morph meiʔ
\morph meʔ
\morph mec
\morph mes
\ps v2
\mtyp v2
\de COMPLETIVE
\gn
\lg C
\qst Present meaning is just guessed based on examples. Morphology should also be explored - this V2 seems to be different from all others in that it does not copy the first syllable of the suffix chain but the full chain including suffixes that otherwise don't get copied. It might form a small class with watt- (MSJ51), which also behaves this way.

\lex -mett
\morph -meiʔ
\morph -meʔ
\morph -mec
\morph -mes
\alt -mei
\ps v2
\mtyp v2
\de CAUS
\gn -आउ
\lg C
\ex Chaŋa kacĩpa kitap khaŋmettose.
\exe The child showed the book to the teacher.
\exsrc VAL057
\ex Ukhɨcɨŋ khaŋmaimeʔno.
\exe He shows us his ass.
\exsrc VAL058
\ex Theke khaŋamettuce?
\exe Why did you show it to them?
\exsrc VAL179
\ex Yuŋmettukuce holau jammai।
\exe Maybe she makes them all sit down.
\exsrc VAL172
\ex Yoʔni thaiʔmettokho!
\exe Make it appear over there!
\exsrc VAL173
\ex Kassikana taĩmettana!
\exe Let it bounce with all your force!
\exsrc VAL174
\ex Saĩli lo okmettoŋse naŋ.
\exe But he's made Saili peel it.
\exsrc VAL175
\ex Akhaita hapmettoko mo na Rameŋa.
\exe Ram makes her cry a lot.
\exsrc VAL177
\ex Kocuwa khumettokho naŋ!
\exe Try to make the dog carry it!
\exsrc VAL178
\ex Maʔmiŋa cha kipmettose. 
\exe The man has frightened the child.
\exsrc VAL014
\ex Iphuwaŋa Rame phakceŋa kipmettoko.
\exe Your brother makes Ram afraid of the pigs.
\exsrc VAL135
\com this is clearly not a V2 as it doesn't have the disyllabic host constraint. It is, however, also not a typical affix since it can host prefixes (and in fact hosts them much more frequently than the stem it's attached to).
\qst

