\lex raŋ
\ps n
\mtyp stem
\de stem; head
\gn टाउको
\lg B
\ex Chadiwa raŋ kharaŋlondaŋkha e.
\exe I visited my father-in-law.
\exn ससुरालि गइहालेको कि ।
\exsrc tangk_talk.050
\qst Werner (2003): A Bantawa Dictionary taŋ 'head'; there seems to be no word raŋ in Bantawa! This is likely to be a variant that is used in compounds. Bantawa has t > d > r / V_V (e.g. *khat-a-ŋ > Chintang khadaŋ, Bantawa kharaŋ), and -raŋ is also the Sambugaũ variant of -taŋ in tree names (also cf. Mulgaũ sɨŋtaŋ : Sambugaũ sɨŋraŋ). chadiwaraŋ seems to be a compound (parallel to nambataŋ), so the rule would be applicable.

